sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: psb1C3_Int
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: psb1C3_IntK plasmid with RFP under psbA2 promoter
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This plasmid allows the integration of a Kanamycin resistance casette followed by a double terminator in to Synechocystis chromosome. The plasmid is intended to be used as a starting backbone for further adition of dna parts by Gibson assembly. It was used by UC_Chile 2012 team to succesfully transform Synechocystis [http://2012.igem.org/Team:UC_Chile]
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: RS1 and RS2 were obtained from Synechocystis genomic DNA, both the kanamycin resistance and the double terminator are from the registry of standard biological parts.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K292003
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Kanamycin resistance cassette and a double terminator
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
This part contains a kanamycin resistance cassette and a double terminator (BBa_P1003 + BBa_B0014). This allows the kanamycin cassette to be functional.
The cassette can be used to design a recombinant vector by gene insertion in a non lytic bacteriophage as the Lambda phage.
In fact it allows us to know if a bacteriophage is modified or not and if the inserted gene is expressed or not. When the virus is modified the kanamycin cassette induces a kanamycin resistance, so the bacteria become resistance, and when the virus is not modified bacteria are killed by kanamycin. This part is completed by B0014 + P1003 + B0014 to finish the transcription before the resistance cassette.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: David Charoy
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Part:BBa_P1003, Designed by Reshma Shetty Group: Knight Lab, MIT (2006-01-23) Part:BBa_B0014, Designed by Reshma Shetty Group: Registry (2003-07-16)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: When we design the bio-brick it was impossible to obtain a functional bio-brick by using the plasmid SB1AK3. But it's worked with a pSB1A1.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: RS1
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Any DNA sequence flacked by this part and BBa_K743001 will be incorporated into Synechocistys PCC6803 chromosome through a neutral double homologous recombination.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: PCR amplified from synechocystis PCC6803 chromosome.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: According to literature, in Synechocystis the recombination sites must be at least 450bp long to allow a rasonably high transformation efficiency, being 700bp the optimum size.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: monomeric RFP: Red Fluorescent Protein. Excitation peak: 584 nm Emission peak: 607 nm

sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Campbell et al., PNAS v99 p7877 URL
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
TAATAA double stop codon added (DE).
Four silent mutations made to remove three EcoRI sites and one PstI site: A28G, A76G, A349G, G337A.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0011
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Bidirectional transcriptional terminator consisting of a 22 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from luxICDABEG operon terminator of Vibrio fischeri <genbank>AF170104</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: In the naturally-occuring sequence there is a mismatch in the stem of the stem loop. This can be corrected via an A->G mutation (at position 40 -- sequence coordinate/not MFOLD coordinate). The above sequence does not reflect this mutation (but the MFOLD image does). This terminator's location cannot be found using some inverted repeat detectors like PALINDROME because it is too short and contains a mismatch. This one was found with the help of Tom Knight. It lies between two coding regions that point towards eachother.
